<tr>
  <td class="diff-marker">&#160;</td>
  <td class="diff-context"><div>The largest flood of [[British Columbia]]'s [[Fraser River]] on record occurred in May 1894, when rapid snow melt caused river levels to rise dramatically, triggering flooding from [[Agassiz, British Columbia|Agassiz]] to [[Richmond, British Columbia|Richmond]]. The flood was significant in both height and breadth.&lt;ref name="History of Flooding in BC"&gt;[http://www.portcoquitlam.ca/City_Hall/City_Departments/Fire___Emergency_Services/Emergency_Preparedness/Flood_Preparedness/History_of_Flooding_in_BC.htm History of Flooding in BC], City of Port Coquitlam website, Retrieved on March 31, 2013&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name="History of Flooding in BC" /&gt; In 2008 Northwest Hydraulic Consulatants (NHC) recommended the adoption of the following flood frequency estimates at the Hope gauge on the Fraser River: 100 year daily maximum flow {{convert|14,700|m3/s|cuft/s|abbr=on}}; 200 year daily maximum flow {{convert|15,600|m3/s|cuft/s|abbr=on}}; 500 year daily maximum flow {{convert|16,800|m3/s|cuft/s|abbr=on}}. The Fraser's highest recorded flow, in June 1894, is estimated to have been {{convert|17000|m3/s|ft3/s}} or within a range of about{{convert|16000|to|18000|m3/s|ft3/s}} at [[Hope, British Columbia|Hope]].&lt;ref name="BCMEOct2008" /&gt; Based on these flows the 1894 flood had a return period of slightly more than 500 years and the 1948 flood was close to a 200 year event.{{harv|NHC|2008|21}}&lt;ref name="BCMEOct2008"&gt;{{cite report|publisher=BC Ministry of Environment|date=October 2008|url=http://www.env.gov.bc.ca/wsd/public_safety/flood/pdfs_word/review_fraser_flood_flows_hope.pdf|format=PDF|title=Comprehensive review of Fraser River at Hope: flood hydrology and flows: scoping study: final report|location=Vancouver, BC|publication-place=Victoria,BC|author=Northwest Hydraulic Consultants NHC}}&lt;/ref&gt; Of the two catastrophic floods on the Lower Fraser River since European settlement in the Fraser Valley, the flood of 1894 is considered to be the "flood of record" but the flood of 1948 caused greater damage because of "intensive development" on the flood plain.{{harv|NHC|2008|1}}&lt;ref name="BCMEOct2008" /&gt;</div></td>
  <td class="diff-marker">&#160;</td>
  <td class="diff-context"><div>The largest flood of [[British Columbia]]'s [[Fraser River]] on record occurred in May 1894, when rapid snow melt caused river levels to rise dramatically, triggering flooding from [[Agassiz, British Columbia|Agassiz]] to [[Richmond, British Columbia|Richmond]]. The flood was significant in both height and breadth.&lt;ref name="History of Flooding in BC"&gt;[http://www.portcoquitlam.ca/City_Hall/City_Departments/Fire___Emergency_Services/Emergency_Preparedness/Flood_Preparedness/History_of_Flooding_in_BC.htm History of Flooding in BC], City of Port Coquitlam website, Retrieved on March 31, 2013&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name="History of Flooding in BC" /&gt; In 2008 Northwest Hydraulic Consulatants (NHC) recommended the adoption of the following flood frequency estimates at the Hope gauge on the Fraser River: 100 year daily maximum flow {{convert|14,700|m3/s|cuft/s|abbr=on}}; 200 year daily maximum flow {{convert|15,600|m3/s|cuft/s|abbr=on}}; 500 year daily maximum flow {{convert|16,800|m3/s|cuft/s|abbr=on}}. The Fraser's highest recorded flow, in June 1894, is estimated to have been {{convert|17000|m3/s|ft3/s}} or within a range of about{{convert|16000|to|18000|m3/s|ft3/s}} at [[Hope, British Columbia|Hope]].&lt;ref name="BCMEOct2008" /&gt; Based on these flows the 1894 flood had a return period of slightly more than 500 years and the 1948 flood was close to a 200 year event.{{harv|NHC|2008|21}}&lt;ref name="BCMEOct2008"&gt;{{cite report|publisher=BC Ministry of Environment|date=October 2008|url=http://www.env.gov.bc.ca/wsd/public_safety/flood/pdfs_word/review_fraser_flood_flows_hope.pdf|format=PDF|title=Comprehensive review of Fraser River at Hope: flood hydrology and flows: scoping study: final report|location=Vancouver, BC|publication-place=Victoria,BC|author=Northwest Hydraulic Consultants NHC}}&lt;/ref&gt; Of the two catastrophic floods on the Lower Fraser River since European settlement in the Fraser Valley, the flood of 1894 is considered to be the "flood of record" but the flood of 1948 caused greater damage because of "intensive development" on the flood plain.{{harv|NHC|2008|1}}&lt;ref name="BCMEOct2008" /&gt;</div></td>
</tr>
