		<h2 class='diff-currentversion-title'>Revision as of 19:52, 19 August 2014</h2>
<p><b>The history of <a href="/wiki/Flood" title="Flood">flooding</a> in <a href="/wiki/Canada" title="Canada">Canada</a></b> includes floods caused by snowmelt runoff or <a href="/wiki/Freshet" title="Freshet">freshet</a> flooding, storm-rainfall and "<a href="/wiki/Flash_flooding" title="Flash flooding" class="mw-redirect">flash flooding</a>", <a href="/wiki/Ice_jam" title="Ice jam" class="mw-redirect">ice jams</a> during ice formation and spring break-up, natural dams, coastal flooding on ocean or lake coasts from <a href="/wiki/Storm_surge" title="Storm surge">storm surges</a>, <a href="/wiki/Hurricane" title="Hurricane" class="mw-redirect">hurricanes</a> and <a href="/wiki/Tsunami" title="Tsunami">tsunamis</a>. Urban flooding can be caused by <a href="/wiki/Stormwater" title="Stormwater">stormwater</a> runoff, riverine flooding and structural failure when engineered flood management structures, including dams and levees, prove inadequate to manage the quantities and force of flood waters. Floods can also occur when <a href="/wiki/Groundwater" title="Groundwater">groundwater</a> levels rise entering buildings cracks in foundation, floors and basements.(<a href="#CITEREFSandink20107">Sandink &amp; 2010 7</a>).<sup id="cite_ref-ICLR2010_1-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ICLR2010-1"><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-EC1998_2-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-EC1998-2"><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup> Flooding is part of the natural environmental process.<sup id="cite_ref-EC1998_2-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-EC1998-2"><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-NfldNR_3-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-NfldNR-3"><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup> Flooding used to be more frequent in spring, but take place in summer <sup id="cite_ref-CBC28june2013_4-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-CBC28june2013-4"><span>[</span>4<span>]</span></a></sup> with flash floods from heavy rainfall. Flood events have had a significant effect on various regions of the country. Flooding is the costliest natural disaster for Canadians. Most home insurance claims in Canada deal with water damage, not fire.<sup id="cite_ref-IBCjan2013_5-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-IBCjan2013-5"><span>[</span>5<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>Floods occur five times as often as wildfires, the second most frequent natural hazard in Canada.(<a href="#CITEREFSandink20106">Sandink &amp; 2010 6</a>)<sup id="cite_ref-ICLR2010_1-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ICLR2010-1"><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> Between 1900 and 2005 there were 241 flood disasters in Canada.(<a href="#CITEREFSandink20106">Sandink &amp; 2010 6</a>)<sup id="cite_ref-ICLR2010_1-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ICLR2010-1"><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-6"><span>[</span>notes 1<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>The 1894 Fraser River flood had a return period of slightly more than 500 years and the 1948 flood was close to a 200 year event.(<a href="#CITEREFNHC200821">NHC &amp; 2008 21</a>)<sup id="cite_ref-BCMEOct2008_7-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-BCMEOct2008-7"><span>[</span>6<span>]</span></a></sup> The <a href="/wiki/1997_Red_River_flood" title="1997 Red River flood" class="mw-redirect">1997 Red River flood</a> was named the 'flood of the century'.<sup id="cite_ref-IJCdec1998_8-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-IJCdec1998-8"><span>[</span>7<span>]</span></a></sup> The International Joint Commission (IJC)'s<sup id="cite_ref-9" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-9"><span>[</span>notes 2<span>]</span></a></sup> 1998 report warned that although the 1997 Red River flood had a "return interval ranging from 100 to 500 years, depending on the location", there was a "statistical probability of a similar flood each year."<sup id="cite_ref-IJCjuly1998_10-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-IJCjuly1998-10"><span>[</span>8<span>]</span></a></sup> The <a href="/wiki/2011_Assiniboine_River_Flood" title="2011 Assiniboine River Flood" class="mw-redirect">2011 Assiniboine River Flood</a> was estimated to have a return interval of 300 years.<sup id="cite_ref-winnipeg.ctv.ca_11-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-winnipeg.ctv.ca-11"><span>[</span>9<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>The <a href="/wiki/2013_Alberta_floods" title="2013 Alberta floods">Calgary flood</a> had a return interval ranging from 70 to 100 years.<sup id="cite_ref-CalgaryHeraldOsborn2013_12-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-CalgaryHeraldOsborn2013-12"><span>[</span>10<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-ABGovBowPeak2013_13-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ABGovBowPeak2013-13"><span>[</span>11<span>]</span></a></sup> A <a href="/wiki/100-year_flood" title="100-year flood">100-year flood</a> has a 1-percent annual exceedance probability (AEP) flood.<sup id="cite_ref-14" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-14"><span>[</span>notes 3<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-USGS_15-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-USGS-15"><span>[</span>12<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Holmes_16-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Holmes-16"><span>[</span>13<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-17" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-17"><span>[</span>notes 4<span>]</span></a></sup> with a flow of the Bow River in Calgary measured at c.1,740&#160;m<sup>3</sup>/s (61,000&#160;cu&#160;ft/s) when the flood reached its peak level on June 21, 2013.<sup id="cite_ref-CalgaryHeraldOsborn2013_12-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-CalgaryHeraldOsborn2013-12"><span>[</span>10<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-ABGovBowPeak2013_13-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ABGovBowPeak2013-13"><span>[</span>11<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p></p>
